</mei>

<!--
VOICING PLAN — Joy to the World (D major, 2/4):

2/4 meter is brisk and march-like. Each bar provides 2 beats for harmonic change.
The famous descending D-major scale melody (mm. 1–4) is supported by simple
root-position I and IV chords, letting the scale motion shine.

Phrase 1 (mm. 1–4): The descending scale D→A. LH holds "334" voicings on I
(D3-A3-D4) throughout, giving a powerful bass foundation. RH adds upper-register
color with 2-note chords, avoiding the melody register (below D5).

Phrase 2 (mm. 5–7): The repeated-note phrase (B, C#, D) is supported by IV→V→I
with expanding voicings — G "33" growing to A "333" then D "334".

Running-note passage (mm. 8–12): The scalar runs at F# → descend through D.
The harp uses quarter-note rhythmic pulses (one chord per beat) rather than
running alongside the melody, creating a counterpoint of stability against motion.

Inner-voice lines (mm. 12–15): "F# F# F# F# G" melody gets rhythmic harp pulses.
M13 features an ii→V progression (Em→A) typical of D-major cadential motion.
M15's IV→vii° suspension: G-major first, then C#° leading to the final resolution.

Final verse (mm. 16–19): Reprise ends on a held D-half-note with full I voicings.
The final bar has 3-note RH (D-F#-A) for extra fullness — appropriate at the close.

VOICE LEADING HIGHLIGHTS:
- The entire arrangement uses contrary motion: when melody descends, LH root rises
  (D3→G3→A2 on structural beats), and vice versa. Parallel motion is minimized.
- M15: IV→vii° (G→C#°) has smooth inner-voice motion: B→B (common), D→E (step),
  G→G (common). The vii° prepares the D-cadence cleanly.
- M7 ascending RH arpeggio (F#4→A4→D5) mirrors the falling melody — the harp's
  upward arc balances the melodic descent.

TEXTURE ARC:
- Opens sparse (mm. 1–4): scale melody needs room, 2-note RH, 3-note LH.
- Builds through repeated-note passage (mm. 5–7): LH deepens to 4 notes (V "333").
- Running notes (mm. 8–12): rhythmic vitality from quarter-beat chord changes.
- Final (mm. 16–19): full textures, 3-note RH, 3-4-note LH, settled root positions.
-->
